The Legal Assistance Bureau in Charlestown, Nevis recently published its annual report in which it highlighted its activity.

Legislators are being encouraged to take kidnap victims into consideration when making new or amending existing legislations. Kidnapping is not an issue local legislation has been designed to deal with. In creating a framework of laws the legislators must also provide protection for such victims and victims’ families.

The abandonment of small domestic animals such as cats and dogs has become a growing problem on the island of Nevis, local veterinarians have revealed. In order to help root out practice, Rhyla Phipps of the Department of Agriculture and Nevis SPCA are encouraging members of the public to come forward with any information that sheds light on the problem. They also called for greater public sensitivity when it comes to pet abandonment.

While products made from edible hemp are freely available on St. Kitts for medicinal purposes, don’t be under the impression that it is available in Nevis to importers of natural and health products.
